            {
                "s2_paper_id": "2d8edf2b72d0924d4f16016674563218299cd44c",
                "title": "Improvements to ICESat-2 Sea Ice Data Products: Enhanced Resolution of Rough Terrain",
                "year": 2025,
                "venue": "IEEE International Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 9,
                "abstract": "Recent developments in NASA\u2019s ICESat-2 (Ice, Cloud, and land Elevation Satellite-2) sea ice algorithm have improved our ability to detect and analyze small-scale features in sea ice. Key developments include introducing non-Gaussian distributions and the introduction of a new data group where heights are computed along constant-length 10-meter segments, instead of the current variable-length segments. Using a fine-scale segment length allows for more precise detection of intricate features, and using an alternate expected distribution allows for a better fit of the photon heights when spanning over ridges and rough terrain. The results from the latest version of the ICESat-2 sea ice data products are assessed in this study with near-coincident airborne campaign data.",
